I randomly remembered this because my grandma asked why my sister was paying me (grandma sleeps in our room) and she did the same spiel as my dad did back then dkjfs

Communication between us is good. We prefer commissioning each other because the value of our works should start at home before we reach out outside of place. We want to repeatedly remind each other of that (esp that we both have low self-esteem)
We managed to clearly lay out our expectations and questions were welcome for both of us. Evaluations were randomly done when the person who commissioned wanted to check the progress.

It may seem cold and it may seem that it could cause a rift in our relationship, which our dad argued, but it worked for years. Commissions did not necessarily mean the payment was money, sometimes we exchanged commissions (i did an essay for her and she did a pubmat for me)

my sister and I acknowledge the value of each other's work and we negotiate on the pricing. we don't offer our commissions and let the other do the reaching out. we have to agree both and we have to be contented with what the other did in order for the commission to push thru

my dad especially did not like that argument. "you're sisters, you should do stuff for free!" as if we don't help each other all the time in other matters. we only do commissions for each other if we know it's the other sis' specialty (me with writing, her with art)

mind you, the commission was around 10 essays (around 1-3 pages each essay). 

my sister and i have been commissioning each other for a long time, with our logic being we should be the first people to acknowledge the value of each other's work.

i was commissioned by my sister and my grandma and dad knew about it. they argued against it, saying "you're sisters. why are you asking monetary compensation with something you can just give for free?"
